 attorneys, as well as testimony from the witness testifying as Ms. Evans, who said she was his patient for more than a decade. Over the years, Mr. Hadden had offered the woman unsolicited advice on sex positions and commented on her body while conducting a breast exam. But, in the last two examinations, Mr. Hadden\u2019s behavior escalated, according to her testimony. She stopped going to him in 2011, she said. Mr. Hadden abused women between about 1993 and 2012, often increasing the level of his transgressions over time, according to court documents.\n\nFederal authorities had charged Mr. Hadden with enticing eight former patients, including a minor he is said to have delivered. Six days before opening arguments on Monday, prosecutors told the judge that their case would involve only four victims, none of them minors. In opening statements, a prosecutor, Paul Monteleoni, said Mr. Hadden \u201cabused his position of power\u201d with patients who trusted him, motivated by his own sexual desires. Over the years, the women have tried to put the abuse out of their minds, Mr. Monteleoni said. One, after being assaulted by Mr. Hadden, closed herself in a bathroom at the medical office and called her boyfriend and a friend, he said. Once her boyfriend arrived, they called the police. A court filing by prosecutors included copies of hurried text messages a patient sent in 2012 to a friend and the woman who had referred her to Mr. Hadden, after an examination in which she said he abused her. \u201cI\u2019m shaking And freaked out,\u201d she wrote in one message. In another she wrote: \u201cI\u2019m in the bathroom don\u2019t know what to do.\u201d Law enforcement officials said that Mr. Hadden built relationships of trust and rapport, softening up his victims by asking questions and then providing unsolicited advice and commentary about their bodies and sex lives. He persuaded victims to travel to see him from outside New York by offering free birth control and directing patients to schedule follow-up visits, law enforcement officials said in court documents. Mr. Monteleoni said Mr. Hadden had admitted that his conduct \u201cwasn\u2019t a mistake\u201d by pleading guilty in 2016.\n\nDeirdre von Dornum, a federal public defender, argued in her opening statement that the case in federal court wasn\u2019t about whether Mr. Hadden had sexually assaulted patients in the past. She said that question was settled seven years ago. \u201cRobert Hadden did what we hope people do when they break the law,\u201d she said. \u201cHe pleaded guilty.\u201d Instead, she said, Mr. Hadden was on trial to determine whether he knowingly enticed or induced his patients to cross state lines for appointments. He should be acquitted of those \u201cvery specific, very technical\u201d federal charges, she said, adding that \u201cno one forced them to make continuing appointments.\u201d Patients chose the time, date and location of their appointments and scheduled them with a secretary, not directly with Mr. Hadden, Ms. von Dornum said. \u201cThere was no premeditation for this abuse,\u201d she said. \u201cCancel him, condemn him,\u201d she said. \u201cDo not convict him of a crime he did not commit.\u201d Some former patients have said they were unhappy with the outcome of the state case, in which Mr. Hadden was charged with abusing six women. In return for pleading guilty to two charges, the Manhattan district attorney\u2019s office agreed that Mr. Hadden could avoid prison and receive the lowest possible sex offender status. Officials with the district attorney\u2019s office have defended the decision, saying that Mr. Hadden had surrendered his medical license as a result of the agreement and that aspects of evidence in the case would have allowed the defense to attack the credibility of accusers. A lawyer for Mr. Hadden had said that she would cite the fact that certain patients were suing him in civil court to suggest that they had a financial interest in the outcome of the criminal case.",
