            "content": "As a subscriber, you have 10 gift articles to give each month. Anyone can read what you share.\n\nHere\u2019s what you need to know at the end of the day.\n\nGood evening. Here\u2019s the latest at the end of Monday.\n\n1. At least 1,200 people were detained in Brazil after rioters stormed its capital buildings. Thousands of supporters of Brazil\u2019s former president, Jair Bolsonaro, broke into government buildings yesterday to protest what they falsely claim was a stolen election. In scenes reminiscent of the Jan. 6, 2021, storming of the U.S. Capitol, Bolsonaro\u2019s supporters laid siege to offices, set fires, knocked police officers from horseback and filmed their violent acts as they committed them. It was a turbulent culmination of years of conspiracy theories advanced by the former president and his allies, and one of the worst attacks on the country\u2019s democracy since the end of a military dictatorship 38 years ago. By this afternoon, hundreds had been arrested, and the tent city where many protesters were staying since the election in October had been taken down.\n\n3. The new House Republican majority faces its next test. Kevin McCarthy, who early on Saturday morning narrowly maneuvered his path to becoming House speaker, is now racing to corral his Republican colleagues on their next order of business: establishing the rules of the House. The measures, which are expected to receive a vote tonight, include several concessions made by McCarthy to secure his leadership spot, including opening up spending bills to unlimited amendments. History suggests that the procedural tweaks are likely to lead to more gridlock and legislative instability. In other politics news, President Biden traveled to the border, arriving amid a historic surge in illegal immigration and anger from both parties about how he is handling it. Also, a special grand jury that investigated Donald Trump and his allies over suspicions of 2020 election interference in Georgia has finished its work. A hearing will be held to determine whether a report will be made public.\n\nYesterday, less than a week after Hamlin\u2019s on-field injury brought the football world to a horrifying halt, the Bills cruised to a comfortable victory over the Patriots. The game, which the league effectively dedicated to Hamlin, felt like a both a vigil and a celebration. The focus, for the most part, was not on the inherent violence of the sport but on the inspiring ways in which the community came together during one of its darkest moments. It\u2019s further proof of the N.F.L.\u2019s narrative power, our columnist writes, which gives it the durability to survive just about any crisis. This afternoon, Hamlin was released from intensive care and transported to a hospital in Buffalo, doctors said.\n\n7. Has Prince Harry\u2019s confessional tour run its course? Harry and his wife, Meghan Markle, have for the last two years been on a storytelling streak: sitting down with Oprah, making a Netflix series and most recently going on a promotional tour for \u201cSpare,\u201d Harry\u2019s highly anticipated memoir, set for release tomorrow. They have largely found support, particularly in the U.S., where they were seen as victims of a reactionary and even racist British royal family. But as more of Harry\u2019s grievances are revealed, our critic writes, the tide seems to be turning against him.\n\n8. Noma, which has repeatedly topped lists of the world\u2019s best restaurants, is closing. Since opening two decades ago, Ren\u00e9 Redzepi\u2019s Copenhagen restaurant has transformed fine dining. But in a shock to the culinary world, it announced that it would close for regular service at the end of 2024. The decision comes as Noma and many other elite restaurants are facing scrutiny of their treatment of their workers. The style of fine dining that Noma helped create and promote around the globe \u2014 wildly innovative, labor-intensive and vastly expensive \u2014 may also be undergoing a sustainability crisis. Our restaurant critic wrote that Noma is surprisingly still original, but he can\u2019t quite say he\u2019ll be sorry when it\u2019s gone. \u201cIts excellence had become inseparable from the culture of overkill that now defines the windswept high peaks of fine dining,\u201d he wrote.\n\n9. As theaters bring more diversity to the stage, sign language translators try to keep up. Amid a recent racial reckoning in the industry, theatrical interpreters from a variety of backgrounds have become increasingly sought after. Some deaf viewers say a mismatch in the racial alignment between sign language interpreters and the actors onstage can be jarring, and a better match can help the viewer form a more immediate connection with a show. In other arts news, \u201cM3gan,\u201d a campy horror movie starring a mean-girl robot, beat box office expectations in its first weekend. The movie reminds us of the amusement and deep unease that dancing robots often provoke.\n\n10. And finally, how to focus like it\u2019s 1990. You may have noticed: Ever since technology has taken a central role in our lives, our concentration has become more fleeting. One study found that office workers now spend a mere 47 seconds on a computer task before moving on. Looking to buck the trend, our Well desk asked experts for advice on how to improve sustained focus. Suggestions include turning off notifications on your phone and making time in your day for a \u201ctech break.\u201d",
