            "content": "As a subscriber, you have 10 gift articles to give each month. Anyone can read what you share.\n\nThis is Diary of a Spelling Bee Fanatic, a weekly review of the game that drives me out of my hivemind. In a good way. Sometimes. Read past Diary entries here, and join the daily discussion in the forum. Speaking of INFECTIVE \u2014 one of today\u2019s pangrams \u2014 I have finally recovered sufficiently from Covid-19 to attend group therapy. Far be it from me to give anyone financial advice, but I am going to buy stock in the company that makes Paxlovid. The chairs are placed relatively close together in our therapy sessions, so I decide to keep my mask on as a kindness to my fellow fanatics. Mrs. Needleman is already seated, as is Rhonda. I take a seat next to Rhonda, and we wait for our therapist. \u201cSorry I\u2019m late,\u201d the therapist says. \u201cI\u2019ve been busy putting up \u2018Have you seen this man?\u2019 posters to see if someone has run into Peter.\u201d\n\n\u201cYou had a photograph of him for the poster?\u201d I ask. \u201cYes, I take a photo of everyone when they schedule their first appointment,\u201d the therapist says. \u201cI just don\u2019t know if people will be able to tell what he really looks like.\u201d \u201cHe wouldn\u2019t stop playing long enough to take his phone away from the front of his face,\u201d the therapist replies. The therapist somberly takes Peter\u2019s phone out of her purse and puts it on the chair next to her. \u201cI thought he might come back for it,\u201d she says, \u201cbut he didn\u2019t.\u201d I look over her shoulder and notice a figure at the door. It\u2019s Peter, and he looks a bit more disheveled than usual. \u201cI apologize for last week,\u201d he says quietly. \u201cI just wasn\u2019t ready to talk about my Spelling Bee habit.\u201d I notice that he has a twig in his hair.\n\n\u201cPeter,\u201d the therapist says, handing him the phone that he left with the group last Monday, \u201cwe were worried about you. Would you like to tell us what happened?\u201d A word that should have been accepted but wasn\u2019t: VINCITE: To provoke an oenophile by smelling a wine bottle\u2019s screw top. \u201cLet me tell you,\u201d my father says over the phone from Florida, \u201cwe have some party planned for tonight. We\u2019re going all out this time.\u201d Whenever there is a Yiddish or Judaism-related word in the game, my parents\u2019 entire building celebrates this \u201cnewfangled\u201d form of representation. I scan the Spelling Bee word list for the inspiration of tonight\u2019s senior-living extravaganza, but I don\u2019t see anything that would have gotten them excited. My mother gets on the phone. \u201cDidn\u2019t you spot the word RABBI? Why did we send you to Hebrew school for all those years?\u201d \u201cYou never sent me to Hebrew school,\u201d I say evenly. The closest thing my parents have to a hobby is revising family history. \u201cYou celebrated Passover by putting spare ribs on the Seder plate.\u201d \u201cRidiculous,\u201d my mother says, as she puts on her lipstick. \u201cYou got the best grades in your bat mitzvah class.\u201d \u201cNot only was I not bat mitzvahed but, years before that, you got us kicked out of a screening of \u2018The Ten Commandments\u2019 with Charlton Heston because you were laughing so hard.\u201d\n\n\u201cThey refunded our money,\u201d my mother says. \u201cI don\u2019t see why you still bring that up.\u201d \u201cIt was just during the burning bush scene,\u201d she says. \u201cC.G.I. back then wasn\u2019t what it is now.\u201d A word that should have been accepted but wasn\u2019t: TRIBUTATTY: Muddy and messy, like a riverbank after a storm. The hivemind\u2019s forum commentary appears to be evolving. Today\u2019s conversation is not so much about why certain words containing today\u2019s letters aren\u2019t accepted in the Bee, but, rather, why certain words that do not contain today\u2019s letters aren\u2019t accepted. This is new to me. \u201cRe yesterday\u2019s Bee, I just wanted to say that a fennec fox is a real animal, and that fennec is thus a real word,\u201d JanineinNJ writes. \u201cYesterday RAITA but not \u2018riata\u2019?\u201d Chans from San Diego says. Still, the same rules apply. No spoilers in the comments, or players will experience the wrath of Woodsider, a reader from New York City, who writes, \u201cMy New Year\u2019s resolution is to flag posts that contain spoilers.\u201d A word that should have been accepted but wasn\u2019t: VELVETO: To rule out the use of spreadable \u201ccheese product\u201d in a dish. Sam Ezersky, the Spelling Bee editor, and I have a tacit agreement: I don\u2019t complain about words that are not included in the game, and, in return, he does not block me on every communication format known to humanity. So far, things have worked out just FINE. Today, however, there is a glaring omission, in my opinion, so I send him a Slack message. \u201cHow come the word LUFF isn\u2019t allowed?\u201d I ask. \u201cIt seems to be a bone of contention on the forum.\u201d\n\n\u201cHow many people know the technical word for the edge of a sail?\u201d Sam asks. \u201cMore than you would think, based on the comments,\u201d I say. \u201cAnd, apparently, it can also be used as a verb if you turn the head of your boat toward the wind.\u201d \u201cUse it in a sentence,\u201d Sam says. I\u2019m not a sailor, so I stop to think about it for a moment. \u201cJust \u2018luff\u2019 it on over here,\u201d I say weakly. \u201cNow you know why it\u2019s not accepted in the game,\u201d Sam says. Thankfully, he decides to change the subject. \u201cHow are your folks? Did they like the \u201crabbi\u201d in yesterday\u2019s puzzle?\u201d \u201cOh, they loved it,\u201d I say. \u201cThey danced the night away, and then the building managers had a screening of \u2018The Ten Commandments\u2019 for the tenants.\u201d \u201cThe Cecil B. DeMille movie?\u201d Sam asks. \u201cDidn\u2019t your mother get thrown out of a theater over that?\u201d \u201cHow\u2019d she do this time?\u201d \u201cShe made it to the golden calf party scene,\u201d I say, \u201cbut it was too much for her. They had to ask her to leave.\u201d A word that should have been accepted but wasn\u2019t: GINFUNNELING: Using a kitchen tool to increase the rate of alcohol consumption.\n\nI am not a superstitious person, but I do allow myself a fairly strange indicator to tell me whether the day will be a good one, sort of like the Spelling Bee version of a Magic 8 Ball. If I immediately spot the pangram after I open the game, I feel as if everything is going to go my way. That is the case today, and, after I type in AXIOMATIC, I close the game and look forward to a peaceful day with no speed bumps. A few minutes later, I hear a knock at the door. I look out the window and realize that I\u2019m going to have to find a better medium for predicting the future. It\u2019s my neighbor, the one who used to steal my crossword puzzle, and he\u2019s holding his smartphone. This can mean only one thing. I open the door and greet him. A few pieces of glitter are still on his face from last week. \u201cAre you aware that the word \u2018flugel\u2019 was not accepted in yesterday\u2019s Spelling Bee?\u201d he asks. \u201cYou know, I played the flugelhorn in my school orchestra,\u201d my neighbor says, \u201cand I was very popular.\u201d \u201cI\u2019m not sure I see the connection,\u201d I reply. \u201cThe connection is that \u2018flugel\u2019 is a nickname for the flugelhorn,\u201d he says. \u201cEveryone knows that, and it should be counted as correct in the game.\u201d \u201cI\u2019m not sure whether everyone does know that,\u201d I say gently. I suddenly realize that I may have been better off when he was swiping the newspaper from my porch.",
